05:33.229 --> 05:36.193
Describe the student body when you were a student 
here. Describe the A&M student body. Where were

05:39.197 --> 05:40.139
they from? What kinds of families? What kinds of 
attitudes? They brought a whole bunch of people

05:44.705 --> 05:48.250
in. All the...

05:48.803 --> 06:03.461
Well, they had some what they called co-op houses. 
Now those were real good pieces. That was real

06:08.367 --> 06:09.388
good. Because what that did That brought a lot of 
people to A&M that never would have gotten here in

06:13.812 --> 06:21.142
the first place. And what it did, now, one of my, one 
of the, we had,

06:21.302 --> 06:37.763
there were five of us that really were in A&M. And 
Thompson was one of them. but he couldn't get the

06:43.715 --> 06:53.668
mass, so he went into

06:43.715 --> 06:53.668
agriculture. But his mother, they were from 
Throckmorton. Throckmorton. They came from

07:02.240 --> 07:03.882
Throckmorton County. And she ran the house. The 
co-op house. And they shipped in All sorts of food.

07:15.970 --> 07:20.715
Everything that they could, you know. And they 
tried to keep them again. And you could get a pretty

07:22.617 --> 07:27.982
good job around here at 25 cents an hour. And make 
some money. I know I made enough to pay my way all the

07:32.547 --> 07:35.810
way through. All the fees. In general, was the 
typical student body, were there some city boys

07:40.415 --> 07:47.066
and country boys? They had some city people in 
them. From where primarily? What cities? I don't

07:52.635 --> 07:53.176
know. We didn't make much difference about that.

08:00.428 --> 08:04.074
Most of them were plain old boys that come off the 
farm. And... Was there a variety of their

08:07.482 --> 08:16.872
backgrounds, of their ancestry, and where they 
went to church? Were there some German boys and

08:18.574 --> 08:22.498
Catholic boys and Lutheran boys? All of those 
people put in

08:24.160 --> 08:35.292
these places they've got up here for, you know, the 
Methodists. They have one there. I know the

08:37.030 --> 08:40.554
Baptists do, and the Lutherans do too. And the 
Catholics, I think they have one up there. But they

08:44.158 --> 08:52.266
kept houses open for the students, even though 
they were in the dormitory. In terms of attitude,

08:52.567 --> 08:57.011
would we have said they were liberal or 
conservative? Very conservative. Hardworking?

09:00.355 --> 09:02.117
Hardworking. But they're all Democrats. Well, in 
that day, there weren't any Republicans around

09:04.688 --> 09:08.213
here. That's right. And you know why, don't you? 
Franklin Roosevelt. No. In my family, I know why.

09:16.584 --> 09:17.005
No. My family thought Franklin Roosevelt saved 
the country. Well, I didn't think much of his

09:20.289 --> 09:27.439
domestic product.

09:31.402 --> 09:39.151
They took the job of resettlement three years up in 
Dallas. But what got me was when I read a book called

09:39.171 --> 09:47.240
Marching Orders by Lee. And they described 
Roosevelt in there. And he was the guy in line

09:52.586 --> 09:57.852
behind all of that military.

09:57.872 --> 10:00.835
He was the one that took He really did a job there. 
But now the other reason is the treatment we got

10:06.375 --> 10:16.731
after the Civil War. Oh, yes. I agree. The parents 
and grandparents. Yeah, but you see the Negroes

10:24.223 --> 10:29.691
got into the Republican Party. And so everybody 
else was a Democrat. That's right. But the

10:34.590 --> 10:44.184
Democrats we get, except for a few, which I know is 
the yellow... Yellow dog. Yellow dog Democrats.

10:47.149 --> 10:49.312
They're the ones way off on the side. But if you take 
the regular ones, they're nothing but

10:49.332 --> 10:56.263
Republicans. And that's why the change over here 
recently has been So complete. Yes. Back to the

11:03.904 --> 11:05.065
student body. Were there any rich kids? Oh, yeah. 
In terms of being accepted, did any of those

11:09.689 --> 11:16.556
differences matter to being an Aggie at that 
point? Why was everybody so accepted? That's a key

11:22.621 --> 11:23.982
part of A&M. Why was that?

11:29.107 --> 11:29.547
Well, They beat the hell out of

11:31.197 --> 11:36.609
you. Was it also that everybody went through some 
of the same experiences? That's right. That's

11:42.363 --> 11:43.345
right. They're all in it together. Do you remember 
many people dropping out of school? Oh, yeah.

12:01.100 --> 12:02.682
Were those the separator courses? No, chemistry. 
Chemistry separated a bunch of them. The biggest

12:12.137 --> 12:15.762
thing we've got so far is blend. We can sell it. When 
did you start using your slide rule? When you were

12:25.917 --> 12:27.079
taught it. When? When you were a freshman. Right, 
but you didn't use one in high school? No. And do you

12:34.910 --> 12:36.431
remember when you got yours? Yeah, still got it. 
It's a duplex love load. And did you wear it on your

12:42.857 --> 12:45.459
belt proudly? Yeah. Was that a kind of a mark of an 
engineer? Yeah,

12:51.945 --> 12:56.449
you had to have it. It's a kind of a... It's the 
equivalent of today's computer. It is a computer.

13:08.876 --> 13:09.937
Sure, sure. I've

13:11.158 --> 13:19.827
got one that's even better.

13:22.790 --> 13:23.351
How much is that? It's a big one like that, 
circular. Oh, yes. Now, for when you're in the fan

13:32.434 --> 13:40.206
business, like I was for 60 years, you just flip it 
around. I mean, it'll do what this thing does. Now,

13:46.055 --> 13:51.163
in athletics, you guys went to Kyle Field. Was 
DeWare Fieldhouse already here when you were a

13:51.304 --> 13:57.413
student? When was it built? I would think in the 
early 20s. Oh, but when you were an undergraduate,

14:01.923 --> 14:07.731
when you were a student here, it was... Already 
built. Describe going to games, you and your

14:08.332 --> 14:13.619
buddies, when y'all went to game in DeWare 
Fieldhouse. Oh, I don't know. It was just a big old

14:15.863 --> 14:17.104
place. Did y'all make noise? Oh, yeah. What were 
the yell-eaters like then? Boy, they were

14:26.818 --> 14:27.679
something. They were, they were some, and they 
were picked out right. They were picked out right.

14:35.496 --> 14:46.727
You had, and you had, that student organization 
was set up by the, by the military. And those

14:48.609 --> 14:54.035
officers, those military officers made that 
thing run.

14:56.837 --> 14:58.459
And I'll give you an example of it.

15:02.118 --> 15:06.524
You know they got this march to the river that they 
did there? You know what ever happened before? I

15:10.650 --> 15:11.411
don't see it.

15:14.356 --> 15:21.245
It happened in those dormitories across from the 
Y. There were 32 of them in there. And Major Sloan

15:26.072 --> 15:29.998
was the officer in charge.

15:39.463 --> 15:43.689
And he was from the Naval Academy. He wasn't from, 
he was from the Naval Academy. But he couldn't go

15:48.435 --> 15:49.898
aboard ship. He couldn't, he just couldn't make 
it. So they transferred him to the artillery.

16:04.454 --> 16:07.939
She was a good woman, but tough too. They all are. 
And so they would have had a big fling ding up there

16:12.525 --> 16:22.659
in that courtyard in between that thing. They were 
just raising all kinds of hell. And the major went

16:27.365 --> 16:32.352
up there and, oh, somebody called him. We called a 
major, and so he went up there. He told the cadet

16:35.779 --> 16:42.767
officers to quiet this thing down and let's get it 
in order. And he just, that's all he did. He just

