And he walked up there and he said, he told those 
student officers, fall out, all of them,

17:05.221 --> 17:14.154
everything. He called them out. He marched those 
kids in formation all the way to the river.

17:28.135 --> 17:29.717
That's where that got started. That's where it got 
started. And that would have been about when?

17:33.923 --> 17:35.025
During your student years? Yeah, it might have 
been. It probably was, it probably was.

17:44.460 --> 17:52.973
And so that's where they really got,

17:44.460 --> 17:52.973
and he marched and turned them around, marched 
them back. They got back ready in time to go to

17:53.755 --> 17:57.480
breakfast. When you were a student, did the Corps 
ever do anything that was rebellious? Did they

18:03.288 --> 18:05.350
ever march on the president's house? No. The only 
time they ever did anything, there were a couple of

18:06.211 --> 18:11.435
times.

18:15.278 --> 18:19.082
Well, you've got another problem, too.

18:20.503 --> 18:25.687
In World War I, you could go to A&M for $1. You knew 
that, didn't you? I'd heard that. You could. They

18:31.072 --> 18:32.113
paid all the fees. but you had to give your you had to 
pay your I don't know if you had to give them the

18:33.190 --> 19:01.965
housing or not but you had to pay your bail and there 
were those two buildings that were in front of the

18:33.190 --> 19:01.965
main building there were two there and every one of 
those guys came back with a .45

18:33.190 --> 19:01.965
and on top of The dome is a hook like this. With a 
light. 1,500 watts. Prexy's moon. Yeah. So what

19:11.860 --> 19:26.596
they did, you could walk into that one on that side 
and just push the screen open like that, and you

19:11.860 --> 19:26.596
could take that old .45 and take a shot at it. And you 
could fire one shot. at that thing, and there was a

19:32.658 --> 19:39.186
hell of a lot of holes.

19:39.206 --> 19:42.230
But that, and then they marked it on the wall. You 
just put a mark like this, and they marked four of

19:43.431 --> 19:49.859
them, scratches off this one. I walked into many of 
those rooms up there. They knocked it out every

19:52.883 --> 19:56.347
other night. Oh, really? Oh, so they did, they were 
successful. The last time I saw that tried was in

20:00.788 --> 20:05.495
1935. A company that I saw, they marched up there. 
And a guy took a Springfield and tried to hit it.

20:19.274 --> 20:21.417
That's the last time I ever saw that. Because one 
day in Mr. Rudder's office, he mentioned that he

20:23.319 --> 20:29.428
had tried when he was a student here. And I believe 
he's class of 32. To knock it out? Yeah, and he said

20:34.193 --> 20:41.843
that that was a very risky thing to do, but you 
thought it was really good to shoot at it one time.

20:42.544 --> 20:45.988
Yeah, but you always shot it with a .45. They used 
the rifle in the last one. And another thing that

20:49.253 --> 20:55.281
happened was that they had a problem with the flag 
on the flagpole.

20:59.345 --> 21:02.488
So you see that flag on that flagpole? The original 
one, I think they changed the flag. It was pipe. It

21:12.197 --> 21:13.398
had big joints in it.

21:16.581 --> 21:18.303
And the one guy said he could climb it. See, they 
just cut the rope right below the leg hole. And so it

21:29.112 --> 21:32.355
went up. And so they, this must have been back quite 
a while, because they came to me, we used to have

21:32.375 --> 21:48.971
kite fights in Simpson Field. And everybody had a 
kite, some pretty good size. And some of the

21:54.816 --> 21:58.900
students knew it and then some of the people there 
They were trying to get that flag down. It was some,

22:02.873 --> 22:09.500
I don't know, it wasn't a U.S. flag or any kind of 
flag. It was somebody's riding on it. So they asked

22:13.463 --> 22:19.029
me if I could fly a kite up there. Or they would get me 
a kite. Or could I build a kite? So I built a couch for

22:23.353 --> 22:24.554
them. I built a kite and put a big old tail on the end 
of it. And they filled it for the hooks, fishhooks.

22:40.866 --> 22:41.788
They got it. Really? That's the way they got it. And 
this was about when? Were you a student then? No, I

22:46.274 --> 22:48.717
was a student. Oh. That was when I was in high 
school. You were still in high school. Or in grade

22:52.683 --> 22:55.487
school, I think. But we used to have pretty good 
guidance like that. And Fermier, a kid named

23:00.980 --> 23:08.090
Fermier, his father and mother died here. And he 
was left here all by himself. That was a terrible

23:14.679 --> 23:18.264
story. His father went, Fermier was his name. His 
father, his wife died. And so the only way you could

23:31.253 --> 23:58.712
uh send a telegram was to go down to this uh where 
there was railroad across there was a tower and

23:31.253 --> 23:58.712
they kept people up there and that was connected to 
the western union that's the only place you could

23:31.253 --> 23:58.712
see him and so uh he uh He went there and

24:00.785 --> 24:14.176
got all the writing done for them to send out, and 
then he just slumped over. My, my, my. That is

24:18.340 --> 24:18.960
awful. He was a faculty member? He was head of the ME 
department. Oh, my. His name was Fermier. I've

24:26.567 --> 24:27.327
heard that name. That happens. So you know, you 
know. While you were a student, do you remember any

24:32.801 --> 24:40.032
tragic events involving other students? Oh, they 
used to have some problems with, I know one student

24:42.436 --> 24:58.399
got killed trying

24:42.436 --> 24:58.399
to, but he was killed right up there by the entrance 
of the college. they were hauling logs or

24:58.970 --> 25:04.458
something, or something like that. He got killed 
right there. That was with the

25:07.983 --> 25:17.698
bonfire. But none of the, and during your years, 
none of the presidents died of heart attacks or

25:17.718 --> 25:24.808
anything like that?

25:27.708 --> 25:29.690
No close family friend? No, no close family 
friend. What about happy times? What about some

25:33.034 --> 25:38.661
happy memories from your student days?

25:42.386 --> 25:54.981
Well, you didn't have any

25:42.386 --> 25:54.981
radio, no TV, so you went and played. Dean Bones' 
office in front of his yard, there'd be five or ten

25:55.467 --> 26:04.177
of us out there playing with each other. It might 
have been some sort of ball or something like that,

26:04.218 --> 26:13.008
but it was not really organized. When, as far as you 
remember, when did your family get a telephone at

26:13.028 --> 26:17.353
home?

26:20.817 --> 26:22.960
In College Park? Did you all have one on the campus 
in your home? Yes. Oh, you did? Okay. So you had a

26:32.171 --> 26:33.352
telephone early? We had a telephone early, yeah. 
Okay. The number was 125. 125. And was it a private

26:40.803 --> 26:44.869
line or a party line? Party line. Okay. All you had 
to do was just call up there, 125, please. And you

26:51.639 --> 26:53.402
did it. Now, on the college, when we moved off after 
World War II, it took a long time to get a phone. Oh,

27:01.264 --> 27:02.626
sure, sure. We had to tell that

27:04.908 --> 27:12.837
repairman that there was a bunch of money under 
that.

